<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100827199757902></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100827199757902><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=100827199757902>RE: Druid soloing</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=100827199757902#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=122872><span id=Sage>lugernet</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>20 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Dec 13th 2:33 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hello Othos;<br>Though I am not a High Level Druid with oodles of experience behind me, but still, I might be able to offer you some good advice. For mana conservation I use these tactics;<br><br>1. [Good trick for soloing or even better, grouping with a rogue (only works on animals)] Memorize “Snare” &amp; “Panic Animal”. This does not work with Grasping Roots (G.R. will only piss off the monster, and force him to stay planted, facing YOU). If you snare a monster, then panic him, the animal will run away very slowly. This allows you or your rogue friend to stab it in the back, without the danger of getting whooped on face to face.<br><br>2. As the others said, D.O.T’s are the most useful obviously at the beginning of battle (So they have the most possible ticks to inflict damage). Now I don’t know if they do less or more damage when the monster is in motion or not, this is the first time I’ve heard anything about that. But what I’ve done in the past, is this:<br><br>“Grasp Roots” on the monster, “D.O.T” it, then cast “Cascade of Hail” it (This will plant it, start up a “D.O.T”, then strike it with 3 sets of ice shards for 27HP ea.). Sometimes the “CoH” breaks the roots, in this case you can snare the Monster and Kite it, otherwise you’re “D.O.T” will keep taking off the points, and you can sit and med until your “Roots” break. Yes, this isn’t the most mana efficient method, but took Yellow this way just fine.<br><br>3. SoW, Snare, and D.O.T is the “Triple Threat” that makes up the Druid kite. If you have Low mana, then snare to pull, D.O.T the monster, run a ways, sit and med, maybe blast it a little, run, sit and med, etc. This is very mana efficient; just make sure you can be safe running around the zone, so you don’t accidentally pull another agro!<br><br>I have many more, but I’ve already taken up a good amount of space. Hope these help you Othos. Keep with the Druid man, they RULE!<br><br>Umptitron Nics (21st Season, HFL DRU)<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Cobler [Half Elf Rogue, 30th Backstab]<br>"It is much more secure to be feared than to be loved"</td></tr>
