<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100909446286147></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100909446286147><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=100909446286147>RE: Druid soloing</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=100909446286147#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=91255><span id= >cookem</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>5 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Dec 23rd 3:01 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Each time you cast a DD or AOE DD spell you give the mob an extra chance to break your root spell.  If they are rooted, I say let the DOT work it's magic.<br><br>I've never heard of DOTs doing less or more damage if the mob moves either.  However, I know the hail line of spells suffer is the mob moves.  Worse... if they get close to you, hail will hit you also.  For this reason, I tend to hold the hail spells for when I'm in a group and there is a tank to hold the mob in place and away from me.<br><br>Also, rooting your opponent in place and casting on them from afar is sexy, but I've found that after you get past your teens, root is way to short or totally resisted too much to even worry much about anymore.  -- druids kite<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
